SIMPLE: specular
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Specular
<hw>Spec"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>specularis</ets> (cf., from the same root, <ets>specula</ets> a
lookout, watchtower): cf. F. <ets>sp⟦eacute⟧culaire</ets>. See
<er>Speculum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the qualities of a
speculum, or mirror; having a smooth, reflecting surface; <as>as, a
<ex>specular</ex> metal; a <ex>specular</ex> surface.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a speculum;
conducted with the aid of a speculum; <as>as, a <ex>specular</ex>
examination</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Assisting sight, as a lens or the like.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy <qex>specular</qex> orb⟦br⟧
Apply to well-dissected kernels; lo!⟦br⟧
In each observe the slender threads⟦br⟧
Of first-beginning trees.</q> <rj><qau>J. Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Affording view.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Look
once more, ere we leave this <xex>specular</xex> mount.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Specular iron</b></col>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Hematite</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speculate</ent>⟦br⟧
